After having inspected the data and changed the column name Homicide rate in Europe over long-term (per 100,000) to something easier to work with, I move on to what big picture the data contains.

Long-term trend in homicides

I use the ggplot function to plot the homicide data. I load Yearon the x axis and homicides_per_100kon the y axis. I provide the plot with meaningful title and axis labels:

ggplot(data = Western_Europe, aes(x = Year, y = homicides_per_100k, color = Entity)) +
  geom_smooth() +
  ggtitle("Patterns of homicide rates in Europe over time") +
  xlab("Year") +
  ylab("Homicides per 100,000 people") +
  theme(legend.position = "bottom") +
  scale_color_discrete("Country")
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula = 'y ~ x'

What we can see from the ggplotis that the homicide rates in all 5 countries are descending over time. However, the visualization is not very clear. I move on to check the rates for individual countries.

Uncouple the homicides of individual countries

I reuse the ggplotfrom the chunk above and insert the facet_wrap() function to split the countries into individual charts. I change the facet layout to two columns and three rows so the trends are easier to access in horizontal layout:

ggplot(data = Western_Europe, aes(x = Year, y = homicides_per_100k, color = Entity)) +
  geom_smooth() +
  ggtitle("Patterns of homicide rates in Europe over time") +
  xlab("Year") +
  ylab("Homicides per 100,000 people") +
  theme(legend.position = "bottom") +
  scale_color_discrete("Country") +
  facet_wrap(~ Entity, ncol = 2, nrow = 3)
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula = 'y ~ x'

This is an easier accessible visualization. I move on to comparing the trends in homicide with the pattern of reign duration among Danish rulers over time.

Compare the trends in homicide with the pattern of reign duration among Danish rulers through time.

#Creating a midyear column

  mutate(midyear= (End_date - (End_date - Start_date)/2))

#ggplot plotting midyear on x axis and duration on y axis

  geom_point()+
  geom_smooth()+
  xlab("Median year of ruling")+ 
  ylab("Years of ruling")+
  ggtitle("Reign duration among Danish rulers over time")

How would you characterize the trend compared to the homicides above?

Answer: While the pattern trends in the homicide rates visualizations above are descending over time, the pattern trend of the Danish monarchâs reign duration increases in this visualization. This means that the monarchsâ periods of reign have become longer as time has passed as the rates of homicides committed in European countries have decreased as time has passed. However, the two plots visualize different periods of historical time (year 1300-2000 in the homicide plot and year 1000-1800 in the kings plot), which makes comparison more difficult.

3) Question: In <250 words articulate your answer on the basis of the data visualizations to the following question: Are we more civilized today?

Answer: In specific relation to the above visualized descending homicide rate patterns in European history, European countries seem more civilized today than back in the days. However, being civilized does not only refer to the rate of committed - it refers to much else besides homcide rates. People behaving civilized are being polite and behave in a calm and reasonable way. Societies defined as civilized have well developed government systems, cultures, and ways of living. The descending European homicide rates imply that government and justice systems have been developed over time - why the countries can be said to have become more civilized. So yes, we have become more civilized in relation to homicide rates, but civilized refers to more besides these rates.
